  1. Notice that the first row corresponds to the whole State of Tennessee. Remove this row and save the result back to districts.
districts <- districts[-c(1), ]
districts
  1. How many districts have a proficiency rate of at least 80% for both alg_1 and eng_1?
districts |> 
  filter(alg_1>=80 & eng_1>=80 ) |> 
  count(system_name) |> 
  summarise(total_districts = n())
  1. How many districts have a proviciency rate less than 50% for either alg_1 or eng_1?
districts |> 
  filter(alg_1<50 | eng_1<50) |> 
  count(system_name) |> 
  summarise(total_districts = n())
  1. Which district has the lowest graduation rate?
districts |>
  select(system_name, grad) |> 
  arrange(grad) |> 
  slice_head(n=1)
  1. Within the Mid Cumberland region, which district has the highest ACT composite?
districts |> 
  filter(region == c('Mid Cumberland')) |>
  select(system_name, act_composite) |> 
  arrange(desc(act_composite)) |> 
  slice_head(n=1)
NA
NA
  1. Create a scatter plot to compare alg_1 proficiency rates to alg_2 rates. What do you notice? Facet this plot by region. Does anything stand out when you facet the plots?
ggplot(districts, aes(x=alg_1, y=alg_2)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~region)

Interpretation. There is a strong, positive correlation between higher grades in algebra 1 and algebra 2. If you score higher algebra 1, its postively associated with scoring higher in algebra 2 which makes sense. Some regions have stronger correlation between the two variables than others. Upper Cumberland appears to have no association.

districts
  1. When creating this bar chart you may have noticed that some districts have missing enrollment values. For how many districts is this the case?
districts |> 
 select(system_name, enrollment) |> 
 subset(is.na(enrollment)) |> 
 summarise(total_count = n())
NA
NA
  1. A lot of rows are missing additional values. Which district has the largest number of missing values (across all variables)? Hint: you might want to look at rowwise and c_across to answer this question.
districts <- districts |> 
  rowwise() |> # this is a group_by() function by row.
  mutate(count_na = sum(is.na(cur_data())))
  
districts |> 
  select(count_na, system_name) |> 
  arrange(desc(count_na)) |> 
  head(1)
